'''Leonardo Salvador Sarao, Sr.''' (April 13, 1921 &ndash; July 31, 2001) was the founder and owner of the [[Sarao Motors]], a company known for designing, manufacturing and selling the [[jeepney]], the most popular mode of transportation in the [[Philippines]]. He is not the first person to alter the surplus [[Willys MB Jeep|jeeps]] left behind by the [[U.S. Army]] from [[World War II]],<ref name=PUV>Blueberry (2007-09-23).[http://phuvs.blogspot.com/2007/09/sarao-jeepney.html "Sarao Jeepney"]. Public Utility Vehicles. Retrieved on 2013-04-25.</ref> but he saw them as a business opportunity for [[mass transportation]]. He redesigned the surplus jeeps to increase its functionality by extending the body to accommodate at least twice the number of passengers and by putting some railings at the back and top for extra passengers to cling to, and for cargoes.<ref name=remarkable>[http://www.hawaii.edu/cps/jeepney.html "Remarkable Philippine Jeepneys"]. Center for Philippine Studies, [[University of Hawaiʻi at Mānoa]]. Retrieved on 2013-04-26.</ref> He revolutionized a burgeoning industry and changed the life of generations of Filipinos.<ref name=tofil>Santos, Michelle D. [http://www.tofil.ph/greatleaders.php?id=67 "Great Leaders in Our Midst"]. The Outstanding Filipino (TOFIL) Award. Retrieved on 2013-04-26.</ref>
Leonardo Sarao was awarded [[The Outstanding Filipino Award]] (TOFIL) in 1997 for [[Entrepreneurship]]. He started Sarao Motors from a borrowed [[Philippine peso|PHP]]700. Though he only attained [[elementary education|Grade 6]] level of education because of [[poverty]], he was able to make the company grow into a multimillion [[Banknotes of the Philippine peso|peso]] [[conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]]. <ref name=awardee>[http://www.tofil.ph/awardee_profile.php?id=17 "TOFIL Awardee - Leonardo S. Sarao"]. The Outstanding Filipino (TOFIL) Award. Retrieved on 2013-04-26.</ref>
He was a relative of [[Leonides Sarao Virata]], a respected and distinguished Filipino economist served as Secretary of Trade and Industry and Chairman of the [[Development Bank of the Philippines]] (DBP) during Marcos regime.
